groupTime440 470.47

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] In 1944, Avery, McCarty and MacLeod published the results of their studies that concluded, definitively, that DNA was the “fundamental unit of the transforming principle”, meaning that they had shown that it was, in fact, DNA that was the source of the necessary information that cells needed to gain new genes or the ability to produce new gene products. Their work established that the transforming principle that had been hypothesized and much sought to explain was DNA. They showed this using virulent cells that they then killed with heat, and after processing to mix and destroy any remaining living aspects of the virulent cells, introduced the left over material to avirulent cells. This “left over” material after the destruction of the virulent cells themselves was then shown to be able to induce transformation in avirulent cells, making them virulent. They also further controlled for possible contamination or combining factors by adding more digestive enzymes to absolutely destroy any RNA, but the transformation still occurred. The only way to prevent the transformation was found to be after the use of a DNA digesting enzyme, which destroyed the DNA. These results established DNA as the “active factor” that was responsible for the effects of transformation.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Following the studies performed and published by Avery, McCarty, and MacLeod, the Hershey-Chase experiments introduced yet another convincing piece of evidence that implicated DNA as being the genetic material of cells. Using Escherichia coli and bacteriophage T2, they were able to show that when the virus infected a cell, it was the DNA of the virus that was injected into the bacterial cell, not the associated proteins. They were able to show this because DNA has phosphorous, but not sulfur and proteins have sulfur but not phosphorous. By using radioisotopes of phosphorous and sulfur, Hershey and Chase were able to isolate the location of the viral DNA and proteins after infection of the bacteria. They found that the radiolabeled phosphorous was the only material that was present in an infected bacterial cell, and that the associated viral proteins (termed “ghosts”) were left outside the cell. This implicated that it’s the DNA of the virus that can take over the machinery of the bacterial cell, using the bacteria itself to reproduce and create more viral progeny.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Erwin Chargaff established that there was a relationship in the proportions of the concentration between A and T and G and C. The three most important aspects of Chargaff’s findings were that the amount of adenine residues is proportional to the amount of thymine residues, and that the amount of guanine residues is proportional to the amount of cytosine residues. They also found that the sum of the adenine and guanine residues equaled the sum of the cytosine and thymine residues. Lastly, they established that the percentage of the guanine/cytosine pairings don’t have to equal the percentage of the adenine/thymine pairings. Using this crucial information, Watson and Crick created a model for the structure of DNA that included seven major important aspects. Watson and Crick hypothesized that DNA is made of two long polynucleotide chains that coil to form a double helix, that these chains are antiparallel, that the chains are “stacked”, each turn of the helix is 3.4 nm long, that major and minor grooves appear because of the base paining, the double helix has 2.0 nm diameter, and, most importantly, that the nitrogenous bases described by Chargaff were paired as a result of hydrogen bonds. This last aspect of their model was crucial to its development, and was made possible using the established relationships Chargaff had already described. The hydrogen bonding is important because the structure of adenine and thymine create two hydrogen bonds, and guanine and cytosine form three hydrogen bonds. Because of these structural differences, the bases pair, creating major and minor grooves in the double helix. While some small changes has been made to their model because of more recent discoveries, the major of the Watson and Crick model remains intact to this day.
phenomenonA Hershey-Chase experiments extended the finding that DNA was the genetic material to bacteriophage.
phenomenonA[comment] The Hershey-Chase experiments are especially interesting to me because I’m very interested in current studies on combating viral diseases and other non-bacterial diseases. The research done by Hershey and Chase set the ground work for modern advances and discoveries in medical research, and even this year the Nobel Prize in Medicine 2015 was awarded to researchers who are continuing to build of their work, discovering novel therapies against infections caused by parasites.
phenomenonB Experiments by Avery, McCarty and MacLeod conclusively demonstrated that DNA was the genetic material.
phenomenonB[comment] Because of the groundwork laid out by Avery, McCarty and MacLeod in establishing DNA as genetic material, we are now able to understand and see the human body in a totally new way. Avery, McCarty and MacLeod used the work conducted by Fredrick Griffith, where he proposed that there must be some “transforming principle” contained in cells. In the present, bacteriophages and infecting viruses are a major concern in medicine, but also hold promise in having potential therapeutic benefits. Some of these benefits could include using a virus to inject genetic material that could compensate for a disease causing deficiency of an individual’s natural cells.
groupTime441 73920.6

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand the basis and the reasoning of the Avery, McCarty, and MacLeod studies. I understand that they used laboratory techniques and procedures such heat killing virulent cells, homogenizing cells, centrifuging, and using digestive enzymes to selectively degrade aspects of their samples. I understand that by using digestive enzymes such as RNase, they were able to verify that it was not the RNA that was responsible for the transforming principle. I also understand that by demonstrating that DNase, a digestive enzyme for DNA, did in fact halt the transforming principle, Avery, McCarty and MacLeod could confidently and definitively state that DNA is the transforming principle, or genetic material, of the cell.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that the Hershey-Chase experiments took the current understanding of the mechanism of a virus to the next level. Before their experiments, I understand that it was known that T-even bacteriophages had their own DNA, a protein coat, and tail fibers. They knew that the genetic material from the phage was somehow transferred to the bacterial cell, where many more progeny phages were made, and then released at the expense of the death of the bacteria. I understand that the Hershey-Chase experiments were significant because they shed light on the mechanism that the phages used to accomplish this life cycle. By showing that that it was the DNA of the phage that was inserted into the bacteria, but none of the proteins of the phage coat, they showed that it was actually the phage DNA that could take over the machinery of the cell and use it to create copies of itself. This is important because it was still unclear how phages could reproduce, since they themselves lack the organelles and machinery to reproduce on their own.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that Watson and Crick were able to establish a shockingly accurate model for the structure of DNA using the previously established results of experiments done by Erwin Chargaff and Roalind Franklin. Because of the proportional relationship that had already been established in previous research, Watson and Crick were able to extrapolate the base-pairing model, and use known factors such as hydrogen bonding and the need for major and minor grooves to create a stable double helix with varying size nitrogen base pairs. I understand that even though this model was published over 50 years ago, only minor correction or changes have been made to this model as new imaging and laboratory techniques have been discovered and utilized.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that without Frederick Griffith, the experiments by Avery, McCarty and MacLeod would not have been possible. The work that Frederick Griffith performed is now regarded as the earliest studies in transformation, and he was able just to show that there was some mechanism by which genetic information could be passed from one cell to the next. I understand that he looked at the morphology after being exposed to virulent and avirulent cells. I understand that he found that injecting mice with heat-killed virulent cells (not harmful) and living avirulent cells (not harmful) actually resulted in the death of the mice. This was a shocking discovery, and one that led him to suggest that there must have been a transfer of genetic information from the dead virulent cells to the living avirulent cells—transforming the avirulent cells into virulent cells with the capacity to kill.

Group: Most Challenging Aspect & Study Plan

challengingConcept Watson and Crick based their model on data from Erwin Chargaff showing an approximate relationship between the concentrations of A and T and G and C, and on X-ray diffraction data from Rosalind Franklin.
challengingConcept[comment] The only reason I feel that I understand this concept in the least depth is because I don’t think I understand how they came up with all of the seven aspects of their model. I understand the base pairing and hydrogen bonds, but I don’t understand the physics because how or why they necessarily came up with the antiparallel right-handed double helix in particular. Specifically, I don’t understand why DNA couldn’t have been parallel, linear, or even why a left-handed helix doesn’t work (even though now we know that Z-DNA can be created in the laboratory and might exist in cells).
addressChallenge I have tried to look up various sources that explain the reasoning behind each of the seven aspects of the Watson-Crick model. I've also used resources such as the mastering genetics activities that come with the textbook, as well as re-reading the textbook sections pertaining to this week's lesson. I found that the most comprehensive way for me to retain the information presented in this course is to take notes in lecture, and then take separate notes from the book. I have implemented these outside resources such as various online video resources and PDF files of concept explanations and practice problems/activities posted via other universities. The hardest part for me is understanding the physics and the organic chemistry elements of the reasoning (such as why a left-handed helix won't work). While I don't fully understand the specifics behind the "why" of all the postulates, I think I have a firm grasp of the understanding behind the aspects of the model that pertain the most to this course.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] They believed that DNA was the substance that caused bacterial transformation. They used strands of purified DNA that was precipitated from solutions of cell components to perform bacterial transformations. The researchers suggested that DNA, not protein, is the hereditary material of bacteria. The experiment included killing the Pneumococcus bacteria and then removing the saline-soluble components.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Hershey-Chase conducted an experiment using bacteriophages and two types proteins: sulfur labeled and phosphorous labeled. Phosphorous labeled the DNA, and sulfur labeled the protein. They injected the protein into the bacteria, and centrifuged the cells. Since phosphorous is in DNA, if phosphorous remains then DNA is the genetic material. The result was that there was no sulfur left in the sells, but only phosphorous, and thus DNA, remained.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Watson and Crick are knowledge thieves because they stole both Chargaff and Franklin's ideas. Combining both Chargaff and Franklin's ideas, they came up with "their" idea. However, Watson and Crick did have the knowledge to put these two pieces of the puzzle together creating one of the biggest scientific breakthroughs.
phenomenonA Experiments by Avery, McCarty and MacLeod conclusively demonstrated that DNA was the genetic material.
phenomenonA[comment] I think it is really interesting that they essentially used bacterial transformation to prove that DNA is the molecule of heredity. It relates to a biological phenomenon because something so small proved something huge!
phenomenonB Hershey-Chase experiments extended the finding that DNA was the genetic material to bacteriophage.
phenomenonB[comment] I think it is fascinating that simply comparing sulfur vs. phosphorous bacteriophages centrifuged results can provide with a huge conclusion that DNA is the genetic material. This phenomenon is so interesting to me because something so small made a huge impact!

explainConcepts[SQ002] This experiment used bacteriophages. The protein layers of the outside of the bacteriophages were stained one way, and the phosphorus in the DNA was stained another way. Once the bacteriophages infected the DNA, the stained phosphorous was found inside the cell and the stained protein layer was not. This led to the conclusion that DNA is the genetic material in bacteriophages.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Knowing that the ratios of C to G and A to T were almost perfectly 1, it was concluded that C was paired with G and A was paired with T. In combination with the X-ray crystallography that implied a double helix shape, it was concluded the A and T and C and G formed hydrogen bonds between the two respective pairs and were oriented in the shape of a double helix with the nucleotide hydrogen bonds on the inside.

phenomenonB Hershey-Chase experiments extended the finding that DNA was the genetic material to bacteriophage.
phenomenonB[comment] The lysogenic cycle is a result of bacteriophages inserting their DNA into the host cell and causing it to become incorporated into the host chromosome and replicating normally (including the injected bacteriophage DNA) and then code for mature bacteriophages and lyse the cell upon exposure to a chemical or physical stimulus, ultimately releasing more bacteriophages.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] They were able to use a series of treatments to remove certain materials from the bacteria until there was no longer any transforming activity in the filtrate. explainConcepts[SQ002] They were able to show that bacteriaphages inject their DNA into the host and not their protein by "marking" the DNA with a radioactive isotope of phosphorus and "marking" the protein with a radioactive sulfur atom. Once an injection occured, the materials were separated. The radioactive sulfur remained outside of the cell in the trial containing sulfur, and the radioactive phosphorus was found inside of the cell in the trial containing its radioactive isotope.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Watson and Crick discovered the genetic structure by using work from Chargaff, detailing the ratio of the nitrogenous bases and work from Rosalind Franklin's x-ray diffractions. They were able to discover the double helix shape with the bases pointing inward and in the rate pairings based on this data.

While this would have likely been discovered later if they had not published it first, the entire field of genetics is based on this information. Without this structure, researchers could only study patterns of inheritance but not the underlying cause for that pattern.
phenomenonB Hershey-Chase experiments extended the finding that DNA was the genetic material to bacteriophage.
phenomenonB[comment] This experiment provided evidence for DNA being the hereditary material, pointing scientists in the right direction for genetic research. This happens in modern research as well in ways similar to the epigenetic discoveries discussed during lecture.

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that Avery, McCarty and MacLeod's experiment was an investigation of the previous Griffith's transformation experiment. They tested a dead pathogenic S strain with a non pathogenic R strain to see if the transformation material was DNA or protein. Somehow the live R strain was being converted to a deadly S strain. The pre-treated the S strain with a protease (which breaks down proteins) and another one with a DNAase (degrades DNA). The found that the DNAase affected the ability of the dead S strain to transform the R strain, meaning that DNA is the genetic material used in transformation.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that the experiments of Hershey-Chase were used to determine that DNA is the genetic material in bacteriophage T2. They knew that when bacteria was injected with this phage it would produce new phages and they laced the protein coat with radioactive sulfur and the DNA with radioactive phosphorous so it was easy to track. The concluded that only DNA is injected into bacteria when the phage attacks and that the protein coat stays outside of the bacteria. By further radioactive labeling tests this was further proved that DNA was the genetic material.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that Erwin Chargaff made the assumption that adenine and thymine pair together and cytosine and guanine pair in DNA. The base pairs do not have to be present in equal amounts. Rosalind Franklin provided that DNA had a characteristic helical structure as shown by a 3.4-angstrom periodicity. Watson and Crick took this information paired with their findings of arrangement with the sugar-phosphate backbone and directionality of DNA to form their structural model.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Frederick Griffith's experiments were the basis of Avery, McCarty and MacLeod's findings. Frederick experimented using two different strains of Streptococcus pneumoniae, one of which (S strain) was pathogenic and killed mice when injected, the other (R strain) was not pathogenic and did not kill mice when injected. He experimented by injecting mice with heat killed S strain and live R strain. The mice died after injection and when he cultured cells he found live S strain bacteria. This showed that the S strain assimilated itself in the the R strain and transformed them to the S type.

groupTime440 64.21

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] It was thought that DNA was too simple to be what lead to the genetic diversity of all life on Earth. However, Avery, McCarty, and MacLeod would suggest through their research that all diversity of life could arise from 4 (or 5) simple nucleic acids. They were able to separate the components of a virulent organism. Proteins, DNA, and other cytoplasmic components were separated and injected into mice separately. When injected all together the mice died, but when each component was injected into the mice separately, only the DNA would cause infection, and eventually death. This showed conclusively that DNA was the heritable trait, able to be transmitted to other organisms, that leads to the amazing diversity of life as we know it.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The capsid of a bacteriophage contains a high amount of sulfur, while the backbone of DNA contains phosphorus. Hershey and Chase were able to radiolabel each of these compounds and observe their interaction with a bacterial host cell. The results showed that the phosphorus containing DNA would be injected into the cell while the sulfur containing protein would remain as a "ghost" on the cell membrane. The DNA would become integrated into the host chromosome, while there was no evidence that the sulfur was transmitted to the host. This suggested that a less complex structure, DNA and not complex protein, was the genetic material utilized by all forms of life.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Watson and Crick showed that the concentration of adenine will always equal the concentration of thymine, and cytosine would always equal guanine. From data about one nucleic acid, it is possible to derive the concentration of all the others.
phenomenonA Hershey-Chase experiments extended the finding that DNA was the genetic material to bacteriophage.
phenomenonA[comment] I am interested in Hershey's opinion on genetic material. From my understanding, he was in favor of protein being the heritable trait. It is clear in the original research paper that Hershey was not happy with the results. For example, the phrase "DNA has some function" hilariously conveys his tepid reaction to the evidence that DNA was the transmissible genetic material.
phenomenonB Hershey-Chase experiments extended the finding that DNA was the genetic material to bacteriophage.
phenomenonB[comment] Not only do bacteriophages exist, but virophages which are viruses that infect other viruses are also found in nature. They inject their RNA or DNA into the phage and it incorporates into the viral genome, which then requires a host to replicate both viruses. This genetic exchange can only be accomplished with something as simple as nucleic acids, not protein.

groupTime440 26.14

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Avery, McCarty, and Macleod published a report in 1944 concerning the chemical nature of a "transforming principle" in bacteria that was the the initial event leading to the acceptance of DNA as genetic material. The group of scientists isolated large quantities of type IIIS virulent cells. These cells were centrifuged, collected, and heat killed. Following homogenization and several extractions with the detergent deoxycholate, the researchers obtained a soluble filtrate that retained the ability to induce transformation of type IIR avirulent cells. Protein was removed from the filtrate and polysaccharides were digested and removed. Precipitation with ethanol yielded a fibrous mass that still retained the ability to induce transformation of type IIR avirulent cells. Testing proved that the transforming principle was DNA. This was proven when the enzyme deoxyribonuclease destroyed the transforming activity of the filtrate, since this enzyme can break down DNA.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Hershey-Chase experiment used E. coli in their experiment. They used a radioisotope of Phosphorous to label DNA and a radioisotope of Sulfur to label protein in phages. Thus, when the phages infected a cell and transmitted their information into the cell, they could tell what was carrying important information based off which isotope was present in the cell. The results of this experiment showed that the phosphorous labeled DNA was present in the bacterial cell following adsorption while the sulfur labeled protein remained outside the bacterial cell. This suggested that DNA is what carries genetic information since it is what was transferred to the cell.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Chargaff concluded that the concentration of A was very close to the concentration of T and that the concentration of G was very close to the concentration of C. Thus the sum of the purines is equal to the sum of the pyrimidines. This allowed Watson and Crick to properly match Adenine and Thymine and Guanine and Cytosine in DNA. Then, Watson and Crick were able to use Franklin's X-ray diffraction images to determine that the structure of DNA was a sort of helix. Watson and Crick were able to use Chargaff's data to determine how the base pairs batched up in the helix structure and offered a model for DNA structure.
phenomenonA Hershey-Chase experiments extended the finding that DNA was the genetic material to bacteriophage.
phenomenonA[comment] This relates to how bacteriophages infect new host cells. We learned earlier this semester about how bacteriophages infect a cell, grow new phages inside the cell, eventually lyse the cell, and then move on to new host cells. This information from the Hershey-Chase experiments prove that the information allowing this lytic activity to occur in the host cells is actually DNA and not proteins. Thus, DNA carries the information needed to produce new bacteriophages.
phenomenonB Watson and Crick based their model on data from Erwin Chargaff showing an approximate relationship between the concentrations of A and T and G and C, and on X-ray diffraction data from Rosalind Franklin.
phenomenonB[comment] Without Watson and Crick's double helix DNA molecule, the process of DNA replication could not be properly explained. We learned about how the two strands of DNA are broken apart by enzymes during replication and that a new strand is produce based off both strands of the preexisting DNA. Without knowing that the DNA is a double helical structure, this conclusion could not be reached.

I also understand that this was not the case when deoxyribonuclease was replaced with ribonuclease, thus suggesting that RNA is not the key for transformation. I understand that based off these experiments, the scientists can confidently conclude that the active transforming principle in the cells studied is DNA.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that the Hershey-Chase experiment relied on radioactive labeling to determine what was transferred from a bacteriophage to an infected cell. I understand that a radioisotope of phosphorous was used to label DNA because DNA contains phosphorous but now sulfur and that a radioisotope of sulfur was used to label protein because proteins contain sulfur and not phosphorous. I understand that by labeling these two substances, the scientists could see what was transferred from the bacteriophage to the host cell. I understand that it was found that phosphorous was present inside the host cells but sulfur was found outside the host cells, thus allowing them to conclude that DNA was transferred and carries the key genetic material.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that Chargaff used chromatographic methods to separate the four bases in DNA samples. I understand that he worked to determine the amounts of the four bases in each source. I understand that as Chargaff did this he realized that the amount of Adenine was close to the amount of Thymine while the amount of Cytosine was close to the amount of Guanine. I understand that through this it could be concluded that the purines and pyrimidines are present in equal proportions in DNA and how the bases match up. I understand that Franklin determined through x-ray diffraction that DNA had a helical structure. I understand that Watson and Crick were able to determine the specificity of base pairing based off Chargaff's model to make the structure that Franklin found in her pictures. Thus, the other scientists enabled Watson and Crick to create their structure of DNA.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that Frederick Griffith injected mice with living IIR (avirulent) and heat killed IIIS (virulent) cells. Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] After Griffith's transformation experiment, these scientists performed a transformation experiment to identify which molecule, DNA or protein, serves as the transforming principle. They treated IIR cells with different enzymes and the enzyme DNase, which digests DNA, resulted in a solution that contained only IIR cells. In other words, no other cells were formed because transformation couldn't occur.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Hershey and Chase experimented with bacteriophages and further proved that DNA is the genetic material rather than protein. They labeled the protein and DNA with 32S and 32P, respectively, and only 32 P labeled phages were produced. They utilized the idea that the phages only inject their DNA into the bacterial cell to use its machinery while their protein capsid remains outside the cell.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Watson and Crick discovered that C, U, and T are pyrimidines and A and G are purines. Thus, a purine pairs with a pyrimidine in an antiparallel fashion. A and T have two hydrogen bonds, and G and C have three hydrogen bonds. As a result, a DNA molecule rich in GC bonds will require a higher melting point to denature it.
phenomenonA Hershey-Chase experiments extended the finding that DNA was the genetic material to bacteriophage.
phenomenonA[comment] Hershey-Chase used the fact that bacteriophages only inject their DNA into the bacteria during replication while their protein capsid remains outside the cell. They utilized this mechanic to determine that DNA rather than protein is the genetic material.
phenomenonB Watson and Crick based their model on data from Erwin Chargaff showing an approximate relationship between the concentrations of A and T and G and C, and on X-ray diffraction data from Rosalind Franklin.
phenomenonB[comment] This model led to the discovery of how DNA replicates because the complementary base pairing provides a good mechanism for this process. Also, this discovery led to the understanding of how three nucleotides represent a codon that codes for a specific amino acid, which creates proteins.

knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Watson and Crick's model showed that there are four different nucleotides for DNA composed of a nitrogenous base, a phosphate group, and a deoxyribose sugar. explainConcepts[SQ001] The results of the Avery–MacLeod–McCarty experiment, published in 1944, suggested that DNA was the genetic material, but there was still some hesitation within the general scientific community to accept this, which set the stage for the Hershey–Chase experiment.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Hershey and Chase's experiment concluded that little sulfur containing material entered the bacterial cell. However no specific conclusions can be made regarding whether material that is sulfur-free enters the bacterial cell after phage adsorption. Further research was necessary to conclude that it was solely bacteriophages' DNA that entered the cell and not a combination of protein and DNA where the protein did not contain any sulfur.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The A:T and C:G pairs are structurally similar. In particular, the length of each base pair is the same and they fit equally between the two sugar-phosphate backbones. The base pairs are held together by hydrogen bonds, a type of chemical attraction that is easy to break and easy to reform. After realizing the structural similarity of the A:T and C:G pairs, Watson and Crick soon produced their double helix model of DNA with the hydrogen bonds at the core of the helix providing a way to unzip the two complementary strands for easy replication: the last key requirement for a likely model of the genetic molecule.

groupTime441 895

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] The Hershey–Chase experiments were a series of experiments conducted in 1952 by Alfred Hershey and Martha Chase that helped to confirm that DNA is the genetic material. While DNA had been known to biologists since 1869,[2] many scientists still assumed at the time that proteins carried the information for inheritance because DNA appeared simpler than proteins. In their experiments, Hershey and Chase showed that when bacteriophages, which are composed of DNA and protein, infect bacteria, their DNA enters the host bacterial cell, but most of their protein does not. Although the results were not conclusive, and Hershey and Chase were cautious in their interpretation, previous, contemporaneous and subsequent discoveries all served to prove that DNA is the hereditary material. Knowledge of DNA gained from these discoveries has applications in forensics, crime investigation and genealogy.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] The Hershey–Chase experiments were a series of experiments conducted in 1952 by Alfred Hershey and Martha Chase that helped to confirm that DNA is the genetic material. While DNA had been known to biologists since 1869, many scientists still assumed at the time that proteins carried the information for inheritance because DNA appeared simpler than proteins. In their experiments, Hershey and Chase showed that when bacteriophages, which are composed of DNA and protein, infect bacteria, their DNA enters the host bacterial cell, but most of their protein does not.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] The A:T and C:G pairs are structurally similar. In particular, the length of each base pair is the same and they fit equally between the two sugar-phosphate backbone. The base pairs are held together by hydrogen bonds, a type of chemical attraction that is easy to break and easy to reform. After realizing the structural similarity of the A:T and C:G pairs, Watson and Crick soon produced their double helix model of DNA with the hydrogen bonds at the core of the helix providing a way to unzip the two complementary strands for easy replication: the last key requirement for a likely model of the genetic molecule.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Griffith's experiment, reported in 1928 by Frederick Griffith, was the first experiment suggesting that bacteria are capable of transferring genetic information through a process known as transformation. Griffith's findings were followed by research in the late 1930s and early 40s that isolated DNA as the material that communicated this genetic information.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Avery and his fellow researchers created an in vitro assay to determine the transforming agent. Avery and other researcher made an S-strain from the heat-killed bacteria. They then used that strain enzymes that destroyed proteins, lipids, carbohydrates, and other molecules, including the nucleic acid RNA and injected it in a mouse. Transformation still occurred. However, the molecules had been damaged, they were not responsible for the transformation. Avery and the other researchers repeated the experiment, this time using enzymes that would break down DNA. When they destroyed the nucleic acid DNA in the extract, transformation did not occur. There was just one possible conclusion. DNA was the transforming factor. Avery and other scientists discovered that the nucleic acid DNA stores and transmits the genetic information from one generation of an organism to the next.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Hershey and Chase used bacteriophage to show that DNA was the genetic material. They allowed bacteriophage to grow in two seperate medium one that has radioactive phosphorous and other had radioactive sulphur. Then they allowed this virus to infect the ecoli bacteria. once they were infected they took the bacteria and used a blender and after doing this they found phosphorus in them. Therefore, they concluded that DNA was the genetic material and not protein, since phosphorus which is found in DNA was being passed on to next generation.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Watson and Crick already knew that the phosphate group lied outside the helix. They saw the paper from Linus Pauling, who proposed that DNA had a triplex helix structure, but it was wrong, since phosphorus are very negative so they would ripple each other and due to this they would break apart the DNA strand. However, using the data from Rosalind Franklin they were able to figure out that it was a double helix and not triple helix and they also figured out that the phosphate group lied outside the DNA structure. However, after looking at Erwin Chargaff data of A and T and C and G always forming a complementary pair, they were able to figure out the exact structure of the DNA double helix. Since the nitrogenous base pairs and are stable compared to negatively charged phosphorus they were able to eventually figure that DNA was a double helix and not triple helix.
phenomenonA Hershey-Chase experiments extended the finding that DNA was the genetic material to bacteriophage.
phenomenonA[comment] Hershey and Chase were the successfully able to demonstrate transduction. They also showed DNA was the genetic material in living organism. Moreover, using DNA is very helpful in forensics and crime investigation.
phenomenonB Experiments by Avery, McCarty and MacLeod conclusively demonstrated that DNA was the genetic material.
phenomenonB[comment] Avery and fellow researcher showed that DNA was the genetic material using the process of transformation. Moreover, this finding of DNA as genetic material made a huge impact on molecular biology.

knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that Frederick Griffith showed that bacteria were able to transfer genetic material through transformation. He used two strains of pneumococcus bacteria to infect mice; smooth strain and Rough strain. Smooth strain is protected by a capsule that protects it from the mouse (host's) immune system and due to this the mouse dies. Rough strain doesn't have the capsule and is therefore killed off by the immune system of the mouse, allowing the mouse to survive. In addition to that he heat shocked the s strain, killing it, and injected it into the mouse. It survived. He then heat shocked the s strain and added it to the r strain and injected it into the mouse. The mouse died. This is because although the s strain was no longer virulent, it still contained the genes for the capsule, which was picked up (transformed) by the r strain, creating more bacteria with the capsules.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Avery, McCarty and MacLeod experiment was based off of Avery's experiment and was to determine whether the transforming factor, was a protein or a nucleic acid. In their experiments, they found that heat-killed pre-treated with protease did not affect the ability of 'dead' S to transform R but DNAase did, therefore they concluded that the genetic material in transformation is most likely DNA.
explainConcepts[SQ002] In their experiments, they used two radioactive markers to label the proteins and the DNA of the phages. The proteins were labeled with 35S (a radioactive form of sulfur) and the DNA was labeled with 32P, a radioactive form of phosphorus. Then, after a set of series of incubation of phage with non-radioactive bacteria, it was found that the radioactive DNA was always found with the bacteria cells and that the radioactive protein was always still left. Therefore, all of the information needed to produce new viruses was contained in the DNA and not the protein.
explainConcepts[SQ003] With using the information from Chargaff and Franklin, Watson and Crick were able to describe DNA as a anti-parallel chains that are double helix and have nitrogenous bases of opposite chains that are pairs, with a few more features.

This newly acquired trait of pathogenicity was inherited by all the descendants of the transformed bacteria.This showed that DNA is the heredity material, and implied transformation in bacteria.

groupTime440 12125.9

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] These experiments attempted to explain the "transformation" phenomenon discovered in Griffith's experiments. They heat-killed IIIS cells, added them to IIR cells, then treated with protease. After transformation continued to occur (IIIS cells were produced), protein was disregarded as the active factor. After the cells were treated with ribonuclease and transformation continued to occur, RNA was disregarded as the active factor. Transformation ceased after the cells were treated with deoxyribonuclease, indicating that DNA was the active factor and therefore the genetic material.
explainConcepts[SQ002] These experiments further supported that DNA was the genetic material. They labeled T2 bacteriophages with either radioactive phosphorus-32 or radioactive sulfur-35. After the separated bacteriophages infected bacterial cells, the cells underwent centrifugation. Afterwards, sulfur (a component of proteins) remained in the bacteriophages but not the cell, while phosphorous (a component of DNA) remained in the cell but not in the bacteriophages, indicating that DNA was the heritable material.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Chargaff's studies showed that there are equal amounts of A and T and equal amounts of G and C in DNA. Rosalind Franklin's X-ray diffraction data revealed the physical measurements of DNA and its double helical structure. Watson and Crick used the above information to create a DNA model consisting of A-T and G-C pairs surrounded by a phosphate backbone, all twisted in a double helix pattern.
phenomenonA Experiments by Avery, McCarty and MacLeod conclusively demonstrated that DNA was the genetic material.
phenomenonA[comment] Griffith's experiments regarding transformation inspired the experiments of Avery, McCarty, and Macleod, which asserted that DNA was the genetic material.
phenomenonB Hershey-Chase experiments extended the finding that DNA was the genetic material to bacteriophage.
phenomenonB[comment] The Hershey-Chase experiments supported further Avery, McCarty, and Macleod's assertion that DNA was the genetic material.

I understand that Avery, McCarty, and MacLeod heat-killed IIIS cells added them to IIR cells, then treated the cell combination with protease. I understand that because transformation continued to occur, protein was disregarded as the active factor. The treatment was repeated with ribonuclease, and transformation continued to occur, so RNA was also disregarded as the active factor. I understand that because transformation next ceased after the cells were treated with deoxyribonuclease, DNA was confirmed to be the active factor and therefore the genetic material.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that the Hershey-Chase experiments further supported that DNA was the genetic material. I understand that Hershey and Chase labeled bacteriophages with either radioactive phosphorus-32 (a component of DNA) or radioactive sulfur-35 (a component of protein). The separated bacteriophages infected bacterial cells then the cells underwent centrifugation. I understand that sulfur remained in the bacteriophages but not the cell, while phosphorous remained in the cell but not in the bacteriophages, which determined that DNA was the heritable material.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that Watson and Crick primarily used the data of other scientists to create their DNA model. I understand that Chargaff's studies indicated equal amounts of A and T and equal amounts of G and C in DNA. I understand that Rosalind Franklin revealed the physical measurements of DNA and its double helical structure using her X-ray diffraction pictures. I understand that Watson and Crick then used their collective data for their DNA model, which consisted of A-T and G-C pairs twisted into a double helix surrounded by a phosphate backbone.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that Frederick Griffith's experiments first illustrated the transformation. I understand that IIR (rough, avirulent, and lacking a protective polysaccharide capsule) strains and heat-killed IIIS strains did not kill mice. However, heat-killed IIIS strains combined with IIR strains did kill mice. I understand that this indicated that genetic material from the IIIS strain was being transferred to the IIR strains, enabling them to create a protective, polysaccharide capsule that could protect from the mice's immune system, enabling the strains to kill the mice.

groupTime440 48.62

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Avery, McCarty, and MacLeod took the S strain and fragmented it. They wanted to know what made the rough strain turn smooth. They fragmented the smooth strain into different biochemicals, including polysaccharides, lipids, RNA, protein, and DNA. Ultimately, they wanted to see what the hereditary material was. When everything, with the exception of DNA, was removed, the mouse died. When DNA was isolated and removed, the mouse lived, proving that DNA was indeed the mode of heredity for cells.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Hershey and Chase wanted to know if DNA was the hereditary material for everything, including bacteriophages. Radioactive tags were used to track DNA and protein in the phages as they transmitted their genes into bacterial cells. The bacterial cell was found to be labeled with DNA, so Hershey and Chase showed that it was DNA that was the mode of genetic transfer for bacteriophages.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Watson and Crick took what other people knew and made it seem like their own work. They took CHargoff's rules about base pairing and Rosalind Franklin's work with x-ray crytallograhy. Chargoff had discovered that the bases paired with each other to make DNA. A paired with T and C paired with G. Rosalind Franklin determined that DNA was a helical structure and that there was a phosphate backbone on the outside. Watson and Crick took this information and determined the structure of DNA.
phenomenonA Experiments by Avery, McCarty and MacLeod conclusively demonstrated that DNA was the genetic material.
phenomenonA[comment] This experiment was conducted on mice and shows that DNA transferred material from generation to generation. The reason every organism resembles the previous generation is because of DNA and how it passes on information. Avery, McCarty, and MacLeod all discovered this.
phenomenonB Watson and Crick based their model on data from Erwin Chargaff showing an approximate relationship between the concentrations of A and T and G and C, and on X-ray diffraction data from Rosalind Franklin.
phenomenonB[comment] Watson and Crick stole other people's work to call their own. This happens so often in science and other fields. It is especially upsetting when men steal women's work and make it their own.

knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Watson and Crick took what other people knew and made it seem like their own work. They took CHargoff's rules about base pairing and Rosalind Franklin's work with x-ray crytallograhy. Chargoff had discovered that the bases paired with each other to make DNA. A paired with T and C paired with G. Rosalind Franklin determined that DNA was a helical structure and that there was a phosphate backbone on the outside. Watson and Crick took this information and determined the structure of DNA.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Griffith worked with two strains of Diplococcus pneumonia, strain IIR which had a rough surface and was avirulent and strain IIIS which was virulent and caused pneumonia. When live IIR or dead IIIS bacteria were injected into mice, the mice did not get pneumonia and lived. When live IIIS bacteria were injected into mice, the mice died from pneumonia. Paradoxically, when dead IIIS bacteria and live IIR bacteria were injected together, the mice died and live IIIS bacteria were recovered.

explainConcepts[SQ001] Avery, McCarty and MacLeod based the experiment on earlier work done by Frederick. They wanted to know what molecule was responsible for transformation. Then using heat to kill these, and taking the remain homogenize cells and filtering them. Other things were added and tested. Eventually they discovered that the active factor was DNA.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Hershey and Chase worked with E. coli and used the bacteriophage T2 that effects E.coli to prove DNA was the genetic material. They did this by inserted the phage into the cell and monitored its reproduction within the cell. They added radioisotopes 32 phosphorus and 35 sulfur to the phage. They knew that 32phosphorus would label the DNA because it contains phosphorus. They ran the experiment, and in the end they noted that progeny of the bacteriophages contained the 32 Phosphorus and not the 35 sulfur. Which indicated that the genetic material of the bacteriophage was DNA not a protein.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Watson and Crick was trying to determine the structure of DNA. They couldn't figure out the exactly how everything fit. They consulted Chargaff's work and eventually knew what paired with what, but still they didn't know the structure. They ultimately used the work of Franklin without her permission. Rosalind Franklin's worked showed that the structure of DNA was helical and with this bit of information, Watson and Crick finished their model.

phenomenonB[comment] Watson and Crick were the first make a model that correctly represented how DNA look. There model is used today

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] These experiments utilized previous findings from Frederick Griffith's experiments with strains IIIS and IIR bacteria. They centrifuged heat-killed IIIS bacteria and methodically destroyed one candidate for genetic material in each trial from the bacteria, such as lipids, proteins, and DNA. Afterwards, they added the IIR strain. When there was no transformation/recovery of live IIIS bacteria, they would know that they had destroyed the genetic material.
explainConcepts[SQ002] In these experiments, they tagged the protein coat of some T2 bacteriophages with a radioactive isotope of phosphorous-32, and they tagged the others bactiophages' DNA with sulfur-35. After allowing each of the groups to infect a bacterium, they examined the bacterium to see what isotope was inside of it. The ones infected by sulfur-35 bacteriophages contained sulfur-35 in them; those infected by the phosphorous-32 bacteriophages did not have a marking in them. This showed that DNA was the material inserted into the bacteria.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Watson and Crick are famous for developing the double-helix model for DNA. They realized that Chargaff's data showed that A must bond to T and that G must bond with C, and this allowed them to create a model with the nucleotide bases in the middle and the backbones on the outside. Also, Franklin's data showed them that DNA must be in a helical structure, and they were able to develop the structure as we know it.
phenomenonA Experiments by Avery, McCarty and MacLeod conclusively demonstrated that DNA was the genetic material.
phenomenonA[comment] These experiments gave us further knowledge on transformation in bacteria, which we've learned much more about afterwards.
phenomenonB Hershey-Chase experiments extended the finding that DNA was the genetic material to bacteriophage.
phenomenonB[comment] These experiments closely relate to the study of transduction in bacteria, and they allow us to see that it is possible.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Before this experiment, it was unclear whether proteins or DNA contained the hereditary factor. In their experiment, they destroyed proteins in their bacteria sample and hypothesized that colonies should not form. However, colonies did form so the results disproved the hypothesis that proteins were the hereditary material.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Hershey and Chase radioactively labeled the DNA and protein materials within their sample of bacteriophages using radioactive phosphorus-32 and sulfur-35 respectively. After the bacteriophage inserted its viral material into the bacterial cell, Hershey and Chase used a high speed blender to separate the bacteriophages from the bacterial cell. Their results showed that the solution contained high amounts of sulfur-labeled protein, indicating that the phosphorus-labeled DNA was transferred into the bacterial cell. This experiment concluded that DNA was the genetic material in bacteriophages.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Erwin Chargaff's rules and Rosalind Franklin's photo-51 provided crucial information that Watson and Crick needed to properly construct their model of DNA. Chargaff's data indicated that the concentration of adenine was roughly approximate to the concentration of thymine, and similarly, guanine to cytosine. This data inferred that DNA contained base pairs consisting of adenine to thymine or guanine to cytosine.
phenomenonA Experiments by Avery, McCarty and MacLeod conclusively demonstrated that DNA was the genetic material.
phenomenonA[comment] Without this experiment done by these scientists, so many technologies concepts wouldn't have been invented. The Genome Project focuses on the structural components of DNA and how we can genetically modify certain strands of DNA. For example, RNA splicing is a technique used to remove introns within genes. This discovery is important to further understand the concept of gene regulation and expression.
phenomenonB Hershey-Chase experiments extended the finding that DNA was the genetic material to bacteriophage.
phenomenonB[comment] Because of the experiment conducted by Hershey and Chase, we now know that DNA contained within bacteriophages is the hereditary material transferred to bacterial cells. With this knowledge, scientists are able to create synthetic viruses for many purposes including: understanding the nature of viruses and possible application for biotechnology.

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] The experiment conducted by these three scientists concluded that DNA, not protein, was the genetic material involved with heredity. In a society that predominantly thought that protein was the hereditary material, this experiment proved otherwise.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] By labeling DNA and proteins with radioactive phosphorus-32 and sulfur-35 respectively, Hershey and Chase was able to determine that DNA was genetic material involved in transformation between the bacteriophage and the bacterial cell. Using a high speed blender, Hershey and Chase was able to separate the bacteriophages from the bacterial cell. They found that the most sulfur-labeled proteins remained in the surrounding solution while the all phosphorus-labeled DNA entered the bacterial cell. The results of this experiment inferred that DNA was the genetic material involved in transformation in bacteriophages.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Watson and Crick were able to gather DNA from two other scientists that eventually proved important for their discovery of the structure of DNA, which won them their Nobel prize. Erwin Chargaff's data implicated that DNA contained base pairs, which consisted of adenine to thymine or guanine to cytosine. Rosalind Franklin's photo-51 indicated that DNA had a helical structure consisting of two antiparallel strands.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Frederick Griffith's experiment initiated the proposition that bacteria was able to transfer genetic material through transformation. By tempering with multiple strains of pneumonia, Griffith was able to determine that some "transforming principle" was responsible for causing a non-virulent strain to become virulent once again. Later, many scientists were able to use Griffith's experimental data to further prove the underlying mechanism of DNA, the genetically hereditable material.

phenomenonA[comment] their model has the following major features: two long polynucleotide chains are coiled around a central axis, forming a right-handed double helix. the two chains are antiparallel the bases of both chain are "stacked" on one other, 0.34 nm apart, on the inside of the double helix. only A-T, C-G base pair occur 3.4 nm length a larger major groove alternating with a smaller minor groove winds along the length of the molecule diameter 2.0 nm

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] DNA is the structural component of chromosome. Avery and his colleagues suggest that DNA, rather than protein as widely believed at the time, may be the hereditary material of bacteria, and could be analogous to genes and/or viruses in higher organisms
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] In their experiments, Hershey and Chase showed that when bacteriophages, which are composed of DNA and protein, infect bacteria, their DNA enters the host bacterial cell, but most of their protein does not. Although the results were not conclusive, and Hershey and Chase were cautious in their interpretation, previous, contemporaneous and subsequent discoveries all served to prove that DNA is the hereditary material
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Watson and Crick took a crucial conceptual step, suggesting the molecule was made of two chains of nucleotides, each in a helix as Franklin had found, but one going up and the other going down. Crick had just learned of Chargaff's findings about base pairs in the summer of 1952. He added that to the model, so that matching base pairs interlocked in the middle of the double helix to keep the distance between the chains constant. Watson and Crick showed that each strand of the DNA molecule was a template for the other. During cell division the two strands separate and on each strand a new "other half" is built, just like the one before. This way DNA can reproduce itself without changing its structure -- except for occasional errors, or mutations.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Griffith used two strains of pneumococcus (Streptococcus pneumoniae) bacteria which infect mice – a type III-S (smooth) which was virulent, and a type II-R (rough) strain which was nonvirulent. The III-S strain covered itself with a polysaccharide capsule that protected it from the host's immune system, resulting in the death of the host, while the II-R strain did not have that protective capsule and was defeated by the host's immune system

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Avery, McCarty and Chase began their experiment with a virulent strain of bacteria that they heat killed and obtained a soluble filtrate that was still able to transform. All of the carbohydrates, proteins, and lipids were then extracted. Separate samples were then treated with a protease, a ribonuclease, and a deoxyribonuclease. Each sample was then tested for transformation. Transformation occurred in all samples except for the one treated with deoxyribonuclease. This lead to the conclusion that DNA is the active factor for genetic material.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Hershey and Chase knew that phages contained both protein and DNA and wanted to discover what the genetic material was. They began by using radioisotopes of phosphorous and sulfur to tag DNA and protein, respectively. Labeled phages and unmarked E. coli bacteria were mixed and complexes were formed. These complexes were isolated and spun to strip off the phages and analyze the phages and bacteria separately. Hershey and Chase showed that the tagged DNA had been transferred into the bacterial cell while the tagged protein stayed behind in the coat of the phage.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Erwin Chargaff used methods to separate the bases and determine the amounts of the different bases in each sample. He found that the amount of adenine is proportional to the amount of thymine and the amount of guanine is proportional to the amount of cytosine. Using X-ray diffraction, Rosalind Franklin was able to obtain improved X-ray data and her work confirmed that the shape of DNA was some sort of helix. Using this data, Watson and Crick came to the conclusion that DNA was a double-helix molecule with two phosphate backbones running antiparallel and paired bases of A-T and G-C.
phenomenonA Hershey-Chase experiments extended the finding that DNA was the genetic material to bacteriophage.
phenomenonA[comment] Hershey and Chase's discovery became an important marker for molecular genetics. After the publication of their work, additional studies were done using phages. One studied isolated and purified that DNA of a phage. The DNA was then added to protoplasts and the result was fully formed phages. This was another solid piece of evidence that DNA was the genetic material because the DNA was shown to contain all necessary information to make the phage.
phenomenonB Watson and Crick based their model on data from Erwin Chargaff showing an approximate relationship between the concentrations of A and T and G and C, and on X-ray diffraction data from Rosalind Franklin.
phenomenonB[comment] Chargaff's findings showed that bases adenine and thymine were found in proportional amounts and cytosine and guanine were found in proportional amounts. He also found that the sum of purines (A+G) was equal to the sum of pyrimidines (C+T). This was found to be the case for all organisms he studied, whether they were prokaryotic or eukaryotic, which I find really interesting.
groupTime441 3947.43

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Avery, McCarty and MacLeod were the first scientists to provide definitive evidence that showed that DNA was the genetic material of the cell. After heat killing a virulent strain of bacteria and homogenizing the cells, the carbohydrates, lipids and proteins were all extracted. To determine what the genetic material was, different samples were treated with a protease, a ribonuclease, and a deoxyribonuclease. Each treated sample was then tested for transformation. Transformation was still able to occur in the samples that had been treated with the protease and ribonuclease, implying these were not important for transformation. The sample treated with deoxyribonuclease was not able to undergo transformation, which lead to the conclusion that the active factor is DNA. Their study showed the importance of DNA in transformation, which lead to many studies to further investigate the role of DNA.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Hershey and Chase wanted to clarify the events of viral replication. From existing data, they knew that phages consisted of approximately 50% protein and 50% DNA and that the production of new viruses occurs within the bacterial cell. To determine what entered the cell when the phage attached to it, Hershey and Chase used radioisotopes of phosphorous and sulfur to tag DNA (phosphate backbone) and protein (form disulfide bridges). The labeled phages and unlabeled bacteria were then mixed and once the adsorption complexes were formed, they were immediately isolated. The bacteria and phages were separated and examined. It was found that most of the labeled DNA had been transferred into the bacterial cells while the labeled proteins had remained in the empty phage coat. Progeny phages that were produced as a result of transduction also contained that labeled DNA. This demonstrated that the genetic material of the phage was DNA.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Using pieces of other’s research, Watson and Crick were able to determine the structure of DNA. Chargaff’s work showed that the amount of adenine was proportional to the amount of thymine and the amount of guanine is proportional to the amount of cytosine. This showed a pattern of base composition in DNA and refuted the previous belief that all four bases were in equal amounts. Rosalind Franklin’s work, improved X-ray data from a more pure sample of DNA, suggested that DNA’s structure was some sort of helix. With this, Watson and Crick came to the conclusion that DNA was a right-handed double helix molecule with the two chains running antiparallel to one another. The based were stacked on one another and were paired, A-T and C-G.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Griffith worked with several different strains of a bacterium, with some being virulent and others being nonvirulent. His critical experiment was when he injected living avirulent cells combined with heat-killed virulent cells into mice. He expected for this combination to have no effect on the mice because neither alone would kill the mice but instead, all the mice that had received this combination died shortly with their blood work showing that the virulent bacterium was in the bloodstream. The avirulent bacteria undergoing spontaneous mutation was ruled out so this meant that some sort of interaction had taken place between the living avirulent cells and the heat killed virulent cells. Griffith concluded that the heat killed bacteria has somehow converted the avirulent bacteria and called this transformation. Other scientists went further went Griffith’s work and showed that it was possible in vitro and this all went to show that some substance was responsible for the change.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The experiments of these scientists followed the studies that Frederick Griffith did. They were all trying to determine if it were proteins or nucleotides that served the function of carrying genetic information. They did an experiment following Griffith's that used bacteria and showed that the DNA rather than protein was the hereditary material of the bacteria. They thought this could be the same for genes.
explainConcepts[SQ002] This experiment followed those of Griffith as well as Avery, McCarty, and MacLeod. They all had the same goal to show that DNA was the genetic material. However, Hershey-Chase focused on bacteriophages. They showed that when bacteriophages (composed of both proteins and DNA) infect bacteria, their DNA enters the host bacterial cell while the majority of the proteins do not.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The key to the Watson and Crick model is the specificity of base pairing. Chargaff showed that A was equal to T and G was equal to C in base pairs. Watson and Crick realized that you could pair A to T and C to G and that it would account for these proportions. They also realized that such pairings could occur as a result of hydrogen bonds between base pairs. They published their analysis of DNA structure and it had seven features.
phenomenonA Watson and Crick based their model on data from Erwin Chargaff showing an approximate relationship between the concentrations of A and T and G and C, and on X-ray diffraction data from Rosalind Franklin.
phenomenonA[comment] This study is important when thinking about the nature of genes and their role in genetic mechanisms. These mechanisms can now be viewed due to this experiment. This helps when looking at base pairings in genetic mutations. This can help us tell where mutations occur, what they look like, how to find them, etc.
phenomenonB Experiments by Avery, McCarty and MacLeod conclusively demonstrated that DNA was the genetic material.
phenomenonB[comment] This is all around important when studying genetics. DNA accounts for a lot of what is studied in genetics and realizing that DNA versus proteins account for genetic material is a huge stepping stone. This opens up tons of possibilities for research abilities to study specific genes as well as disorders and family inheritance.

phenomenonB[comment] Although the sources used were practically stolen information for most of Watson and Crick's ideas, their model helped identify the fact of how DNA was shaped, with purines and pyrimidines connected by a phosphate backbone and hydrogen bonds for a double helix.

groupTime440 31.8

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] These experiments were done by injecting virulent pneumonia strains into mice. If these viruses had a rough coat the mouse's immune system could fight the virus, but if it had a smooth coat, then the mouse was unable to fight and became sick and died. When they heat-killed the virus, something interesting happened. The heat-killed smooth strain did not kill the mouse, but when the heat-killed smooth strain mixed with the live rough strain was injected, the mouse died. This suggested that somehow genetic material from the smooth strain was transmitted to the rough strain.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Hershey and Chase used radioactive Phosphorous and Sulfur to label DNA and the viral protein coats respectively. They did this by injecting bacteria with the viruses, let them inject their material into the bacteria, labeled them, and then let them reproduce. After the bacteria reproduced, they found that phosphorous had been transmitted to the next generation and the sulfur had not. Therefore, DNA was also the genetic material in bacteriophage.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Chargaff's data showed that in all the different species he examined (including humans) A and T have very similar proportions as do C and G, so there is roughly the same amount of A as T and C as G. Rosalind Franklin had produced a very clear image through X-ray crystallography that, when interpreted by someone who knew how, showed that the DNA molecule is a double helix. Watson and Crick used this information to form the model of DNA that still stands strong today.
phenomenonA Experiments by Avery, McCarty and MacLeod conclusively demonstrated that DNA was the genetic material.
phenomenonA[comment] This relates to transduction, which was how the DNA was picked up by the bacteria from an outside source.
phenomenonB Watson and Crick based their model on data from Erwin Chargaff showing an approximate relationship between the concentrations of A and T and G and C, and on X-ray diffraction data from Rosalind Franklin.
phenomenonB[comment] X-ray diffraction is very interesting. I would like to know more about how Rosalind Franklin was able to "read" the picture and know DNA was a double helix, and what other molecules, like proteins, would look like with X-ray diffraction.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Avery, McCarty, and MacLeod used virulent proteins and injected them into mice. They discovered that just because the virulent proteins were heat killed and mixed with the non-virulent proteins would cause the death of mice even though the proteins that would cause death were dead before they even were injected into the mice. This meant that the proteins had to have some way of transferring the genetic material even after death. The only way that could have happened was if there was a crossing over of the DNA that held the virulent genetic material that caused death.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Hershey-Chase experiments took radio labels phosphorus and sulfur. The theory was that the radio labeled phosphorus would bond to the phosphodiester back bone of DNA and make it detectable if it was passed on to the next generation. The sulfur was bond with the sulfur in the proteins that wasn't in DNA and if it held the genetic material then it would pass the radio labeled sulfur onto the next generation of cells.
explainConcepts[SQ003] yes they were successful in producing the correct model of the double helix DNA, but they were only able to do so with the help of Rosalind Franklin and her abilities of perfect x-ray crystallography. As well as the knowledge of how the four bases always paired up with the same ones (G-C & A-T). They got lucky enough to get the right information at the right time and they were smart enough to know how valuable that information was. With this information, they were able to successfully model the proper form of DNA which turned out to be a double helix.
phenomenonA Hershey-Chase experiments extended the finding that DNA was the genetic material to bacteriophage.
phenomenonA[comment] The use of radio labeled bacteriophages to determine the piece of the cell that held the DNA was a huge achievement for the world. It has allowed the genetic mapping of diseases and numerous other syndromes that plague the human race.
phenomenonB Watson and Crick based their model on data from Erwin Chargaff showing an approximate relationship between the concentrations of A and T and G and C, and on X-ray diffraction data from Rosalind Franklin.
phenomenonB[comment] Watson and Crick were only able to model the structure of DNA with the information of Chargaff determining the bonding of the bases, as well as the x-ray crystallography from Franklin and her lab.

explainConcepts[SQ001] This is experiment attempted to determine whether DNA or protein was the molecule of inheritance. To do this, they noted whether or not mice would die when injected with a phage. One strain has its protein denatured while the other had its DNA denatured. The phage with DNA denatured was unable to pass down its genome to create new viruses and thus the mice survived.
explainConcepts[SQ002] This experiment was vital in determining that DNA was the molecule of inheritance. The DNA and protein of a phage were both marked with radioactive isotopes. The researchers then determined which radioactive isotope made it into the infected cell. This allowed them to conclude that DNA was most likely the molecule of inheritance.
explainConcepts[SQ003] This was possibly the most important work in the field of genetics during the 20th century. When the molecule was successfully modeled thanks to the work of many people, it greatly expanded the current understand of genetics, propelling the field forward.

explainConcepts[SQ003] Watson and Crick used the data obtained from the base pairing data from Chargaff as well as Rosalind Franklin's photo 51. This allowed them the determine the DNA was a double helix and that the bases are paired in a complementary fashion.

Other experiments were also conducted at the Rockefeller Institute where researchers continued to study transformation in the years that followed. phenomenonB[comment] Many other researchers took place in the race for the structure of DNA. Linus Pauling also proposed a model of DNA, but with a triple helix and not the correct double helix.

groupTime440 103.04

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] In 1944, Avery, McCarty and McLeod concluded after extensive research that DNA was in fact the source of genetic information for cells. To show this, they used virulent cells which they heated to kill any living aspects of the cells. After processing, they introduced the "left overs" of the virulent cells were introduced to avirulent cells. The "left over" material was still able to transform avirulent cells to become virulent, even though the virulent cells had been destroyed. They controlled for possible contamination of the sample by adding an enzyme that would destroy any RNA, but the transformation still occurred. The only way to stop the transformation was by adding a DNA degrading enzyme. Thus they concluded that DNA was the "active factor" in the transfer of genetic material.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The Hershey-Chase experiments used an E. coli bacteria cell and a bacteriophage T2 to show that it was the DNA of the virus that was injected into the cell and not the associated proteins. They determined this by using radioisotopes of phosphorus and sulfur to figure out the location of viral DNA and proteins after the infecting the bacteria. DNA contains phosphorus but not sulfur and proteins have sulfur but not phosphorus. They found that the radiolabeled phosphorus remained inside the infected bacteria and the sulfur remained outside the cell. This indicated that the viral DNA was able to take over the bacterial cell machinery by using the bacteria itself to reproduce more viral progeny.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Erwin Chargaff found that the amount of adenine residues was proportional to the amount of thymine resides and the amount of guanine residues was proportional to the amount of cytosine residues. He also found that the sum of the A and G residues equaled the sum of the C and T residues, but the percentage of A/T pairings don't necessarily equal the G/C pairings. Watson and Crick used Chargaff's findings to create a model for the structure of DNA. They hypothesized that DNA was made of two long polynucleotide chains that coil to form a double helix. The chains run antiparallel and are "stacked" on top of each other, each turn of the helix is 3.4 nm long, and the helix is 2.0 nm wide. There are major and minor grooves that appear due to base pairing. They also hypothesized that the bases described by Chargaff were paired by hydrogen bonds. Their model still stays in tact today, with a few small changes.
phenomenonA Watson and Crick based their model on data from Erwin Chargaff showing an approximate relationship between the concentrations of A and T and G and C, and on X-ray diffraction data from Rosalind Franklin.
phenomenonA[comment] The Watson and Crick model is still in use today. As technology gets better, we have discovered more about DNA structure and made modifications to their model, but for the most part, their original model remains the standard. Their work was pivotal in the study of DNA.
phenomenonB Experiments by Avery, McCarty and MacLeod conclusively demonstrated that DNA was the genetic material.
phenomenonB[comment] The experiments by Avery, McCarty and MacLeod helped us to understand the the "transforming principle" in cells described by Frederick Griffith better. Today, bacteriophages and viral infections are a major concern in medicine. Using the principles described by Avery, McCarty, and MacLeod, we can better understand how viral DNA is transferred and replicated and from that create treatments. For example, vaccines or using a virus to inject genetic material that could compensate for a disease causing deficiency of an individual’s natural cells.

knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that Watson and Crick were able to create an accurate model of DNA by using the base pair findings of Erwin Chargaff. I understand that a few modifications have been made to their model as we gain more information, but their model remains largely in tact today.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that without Frederick Griffith, the experiments by Avery, McCarty and MacLeod would not have been possible. I understand that he looked at the morphology after being exposed to virulent and avirulent cells. I understand that he found that injecting mice with heat-killed virulent cells (not harmful) and living avirulent cells (not harmful) actually resulted in the death of the mice. This was a shocking discovery, and one that led him to suggest that there must have been a transfer of genetic information from the dead virulent cells to the living avirulent cells—transforming the avirulent cells into virulent cells with the capacity to kill.

By infecting unlabeled bacteria with labeled phages, the two scientists concluded that DNA was the genetic material because 32P was found inserted into the bacteria.

Franklin's data suggested that a helix was the structure of DNA and confirmed the distance between the bases. Watson and Crick used the results from these scientists to determine that DNA had a double helix and that pairing A with T and C with G would account for the proportions noted by Chargaff.
