groupTime440 28.66

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] These experiments was the initial event that lead to the acceptance of DNA as the genetic material. Their work was the first direct experimental proof that DNA is the biomolecule responsible for heredity, no proteins. They ran experiments on several strains of pneumonia bacterium, some virulent and some avirulent. The difference depended on the polysaccharide capsule around the bacterial. The Virulent had the capsule and the avirulent did not. Virulent bacteria were not easily engulfed, so they multiplied and caused pneumonia.
explainConcepts[SQ002] This study was of the Escherichia coli and one of its infecting viruses, bacteriophage T2. The virus consisted of a protein coat surrounding DNA. They knew that the phage’s external structure was composed of a hexagonal head and a tail. The phage adsorbs to the bacterial cell, and then some genetic component of the phage enters the bacterial cell. Following infection, the viral component takes over the host and causes viral reproduction. In a reasonably short time, many new phages are made. The bacterial cell is then lysed, which releases the progeny viruses. This is known as the lytic cycle. This helped prove that DNA was the genetic material because the virus DNA was copied and spread.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Erwin Chargaff and his colleagues used chromatographic methods to separate the four bases in DNA from various organisms. They then used quantitative methods to determine the amounts of the four bases. This data was critical to the success of Watson and Crick, as they came up with the double helical model of DNA. The amount of adenine residues is proportional to the amount of thymine residues, and the amount of guanine residues is proportional to the amount of cytosine residues. The data provided the initial clue to the DNA puzzle for Watson and Crick. When fibers of a DNA molecule are subjected to X-ray bombardment, the X rays scatter in a pattern that depends on the molecule’s atomic structure. The pattern of diffraction can be captured as spots on photographic film and analyzed for clues to the overall shape of and regularities within the molecule. Rosalind Franklin obtained X-ray data from purified samples of DNA, which suggested that the structure of DNA was some sort of helix. However, she did not propose a definitive model and her work was wrongfully given and used by Watson and Crick.
phenomenonA Experiments by Avery, McCarty and MacLeod conclusively demonstrated that DNA was the genetic material.
phenomenonA[comment] The experiments that proved that DNA was the genetic material relates to the real world now because there are still many cases of pneumonia, which was what they tested. Pneumonia that causes the illness has the capsule, which allowed them to survive in the host and not be able to be engulfed and killed by the immense system.
phenomenonB Hershey-Chase experiments extended the finding that DNA was the genetic material to bacteriophage.
phenomenonB[comment] The hershey and Chase experiment shows hoe bacteriophages use its DNA to replicate and infect the host by creating more progeny through the lytic cycle. Many viruses like the common cold and the flu replicate and infect people this way.

groupTime440 55.33

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Avery, McCarty and MacLeod discovered what the transformation factor was in the bacteria that killed the mice. They thought that it was either a protein or a nucleic acid. They used protease to treat heat killed S strain bacteria to see if it inhibited the transformation of the R strain bacteria, but it did not. So, they treated it with DNAase and the transformation was inhibited. This concluded that DNA was the genetic material.
explainConcepts[SQ002] In Hershey and Chase's experiment, they used two radioactive markers to label the protein and DNA of a bacteriaphage. They allowed the bacteriaphages to infect the bacteria, and then they put the cells in a centrifuge. Once the cells were separated, the bacteria was found with the DNA marker, so they knew that the DNA was injected by the bacteriaphages. This allowed them to conclude that DNA was the genetic material.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Watson and Crick were able to build the model of DNA from the information gathered by Erwin Chargaff and Rosalind Franklins photograph. The photograph showed the shape of DNA, so they had to figure out how the bases went together the form the double helix. From Erwin Chargaff's work, they used the base pairing data to put the bases together so that a double helix could be made. They paired adenine with thymine and guanine with cytosine. This allowed them to construct the model of DNA as a right handed double helix.
phenomenonA Watson and Crick based their model on data from Erwin Chargaff showing an approximate relationship between the concentrations of A and T and G and C, and on X-ray diffraction data from Rosalind Franklin.
phenomenonA[comment] By using the model that Watson and Crick constructed, the mechanism of DNA replication becomes apparent. The helix can unwind and allow replication to occur on each of its two strands. One of the strands would be the leading strand and the other would be the lagging strand. This structure provides for this mechanism of DNA replication.
phenomenonB Hershey-Chase experiments extended the finding that DNA was the genetic material to bacteriophage.
phenomenonB[comment] Hershey and Chase's experiments show how DNA is the genetic material due to the transfer of the radioactive labeled DNA into the bacteria. This shows an important biological phenomenon of how viruses infect cells and transfer their genetic material to allow an infection to spread throughout the body. Not only does it demonstrate the transfer of genetic material, but also that DNA is the molecule that allows for the virus to spread.

Then he heat treated the smooth strain to denature the protein coat and mixed this with the rough strain. He injected this into the mice and the mice died. This allowed him to conclude that a transforming factor was present and that DNA could be transferred from the smooth strain to the rough strain, which killed the mice.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Avery, McCarty, and MacLeod demonstrated that DNA was the genetic material by injecting mice with various strains of bacteria. Only the bacteria that had the DNA destroyed (compared to the bacteria that had the RNA, lipids, polysaccharides, and protein) lived, because the genetic material was destroyed and could not harm the mouse. This proved that DNA was the genetic material in cells.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The Hershey-Chase experiment also supported that DNA was the genetic material within the cell by determining if bacteriophages injected protein (sulfur) or DNA (phosphorus) into the cell. Since phosphorus was injected, the conclusion was that DNA was the hereditary material injected into the cell.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Watson and Crick (along with other scientists) determined that 4 base pairs were responsible for comprising the DNA molecule. X ray diffraction aided their research by making it possible to know that DNA was a double helix. Calculations have been performed and the percentage of AT pairs and GC pairs are not equal, which also contributed to creating the model of DNA.
phenomenonA Watson and Crick based their model on data from Erwin Chargaff showing an approximate relationship between the concentrations of A and T and G and C, and on X-ray diffraction data from Rosalind Franklin.
phenomenonA[comment] In order to know how our DNA is passed from parent to offspring, one must know the structure of DNA. In addition, one must know the base pairing, how the molecule opens, etc) Without this information, our knowledge of DNA would be extremely retarded. This information allows scientists to know how genetic disorders such as Trisomy 21 and Edwards occur.
phenomenonB Experiments by Avery, McCarty and MacLeod conclusively demonstrated that DNA was the genetic material.
phenomenonB[comment] Without this pioneering experiment, we would not know that DNA was the genetic material. Prior, scientists thought that the material may be proteins. By having the knowledge that hereditary material is DNA, scientists could research into the structure and components of DNA as well as how it replicates and is inherited. If we never found out that DNA was the genetic material, our knowledge of the scientific would would be highly deficient. This topic relates to meiosis and mitosis as well as the diseases that occur due to nondisjunction.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Avery, McCarty, and MacLeod illustrated that DNA was the genetic material by showing that DNA is the material that is capable of transforming bacteria. The idea of DNA transforming bacteria signifies that cells take up extraneous genetic material from their surroundings. Since DNA is taken up through the cell membranes, it is known as the genetic material.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Hershey and Chase demonstrated and perpetuated the idea that DNA is the genetic material. At this point in time, many people believed that proteins were the genetic material due to their complex structure. However, since these researchers used radioactive phosphorus, the backbone structure of DNA, and radioactive sulfur, a component of proteins, they were able to distinguish which element appeared as the universal genetic material among all organisms.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Using the information from Chargaff and Franklin, Watson and Crick demonstrated the structure of DNA. DNA incorporates complementary pairing (A pairs with T and C pairs with G). Additionally, the genetic material is created with a phosphate backbone in a double-helix fashion.
phenomenonA Watson and Crick based their model on data from Erwin Chargaff showing an approximate relationship between the concentrations of A and T and G and C, and on X-ray diffraction data from Rosalind Franklin.
phenomenonA[comment] When DNA does not pair properly, if the elements of the material do not match up like they're supposed to, the material is capable of returning to the mutation and correcting itself.
phenomenonB Hershey-Chase experiments extended the finding that DNA was the genetic material to bacteriophage.
phenomenonB[comment] Oftentimes, more complex materials may not have more significant functions within the human body. In other words, just because proteins are more complex than DNA, that should not be evidence that protein is the genetic material.

groupTime440 39.47

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The Avery, McCarty, and MacLeod experiment utilized a a procedure known as the "transforming principle." They began with heat killing a virulent strain of bacteria. Next, they isolated the carbohydrates, lipids, and proteins from the dead mixture. They then proceeded to mix these virulent strain ingredients with an avirulent bacteria and different digesting enzymes. The enzymes used digested particular part of the mixture: protease (protein), RNase (RNA), and DNase (DNA). If transformation occurred in the final product, they were able to conclude that the virulent strain of genetic information was taken up by the avirulent bacteria. Their goal was to isolate the genetic information, and in order to prove this, they needed to find which part of the mixture needed to be digested in order for no transformation to occur. They found that the protease and RNase added to each test resulted in a transforming bacteria. When the DNase was added to the test, the resulting bacteria did not transform, concluding that DNA was the source of genetic information.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The Hershey-Chase experiment involved using phage marked with radioisotopes to determine if DNA or proteins were the genetic information infecting bacteria. The proteins of the phage were marked with a sulfur radioisotope. The DNA was marked with a phosphorous isotope. After procuring infected bacteria, they completely separated the phages from the bacteria. Their results showed that the bacteria, once infected, contained the phosphorous isotopes, and the sulfur isotopes remained in the phage "ghosts."
explainConcepts[SQ003] By using x-ray diffraction, Watson and Crick were able to composite a picture of the structure of the DNA double helix. The molecules are subjected to x-ray, and the scattering of the x-rays is dependent of the molecules being examined. They used Chargaff's data regarding the concentrations of the purines and pyrimidines to distinguish the A-T/C-G nitrogenous bonds within the helix. These base pairings they proved are hydrogen bonds. The proved at the molecular level that the adenine will only bond to the thymine, and cytosine will only bond at the guanine, which produces the final structure. This pairing is known as complementarity.
phenomenonA Watson and Crick based their model on data from Erwin Chargaff showing an approximate relationship between the concentrations of A and T and G and C, and on X-ray diffraction data from Rosalind Franklin.
phenomenonA[comment] DNA is a double helix structure arising from phosphate-sugar backbones running antiparallel. Within these backbones are nitrogenous base pairings that occur in complementarity, or A-T/C-G hydrogen bonds. These bonds occur in particular patterns, and code for proteins synthesis. This concept was taught to me from honors biology in high school.
phenomenonB Experiments by Avery, McCarty and MacLeod conclusively demonstrated that DNA was the genetic material.
phenomenonB[comment] Early research of genetics initially thought proteins were the genetic information carried by individual organisms. Lab research with bacteria, and means which genetic information is absorbed by genetic information has intrigued me since I started learning biology.
groupTime441 7081.22

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] The "transforming principle" allowed their experiments to conclude that DNA is the source of genetic information of life. Bacteria is capable of absorbing DNA and proteins from its surroundings. This allowed Avery, McCarty, and MacLeod to identify the particular source of genetic information.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Hershey and Chase narrowed down the source of genetic information to one of either two components: proteins or DNA. Phages were marked with isotopes, and these isotopes were either marked on the protein of the phage or the DNA of the phage. Once the marked DNA was obtained from infected bacteria, they were able to conclude that DNA, to protein, was the source of genetic information.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Using x-ray diffraction, Watson and Crick were able to image the structure of DNA, proving it was a double helix structure of nitrogenous bases. The bases were either an adenine-thymine bond or a cytosine-guanine bond. They deduced this due to the fact that they were hydrogen bonds, and the bond structure was specific to these molecules.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Griffith proved that avirulent bacteria are capable of absorbing genetic information from virulent strains (outside the cell) and become transformed to a virulent strain of bacteria. Knowing this allowed scientists to determine which part of the cell that gets absorbed by the bacteria contains the genetic information.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Avery, MacLeod, and McCarty studied the factor that could change a lethal strain into a non-lethal strain into a lethal strain. Their experiments definitively proved that the transforming principle was DNA.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The experiments by Hershey and Chase demonstrated that DNA was the hereditary material. Using T2 bacteriophage, they showed that DNA and not protein entered the bacterial cell. Since new T2 phage particles were produced inside the cell, it was concluded that DNA was responsible for its development. Although quite conclusive at the time, scientists now realize that the fact that the DNA was actually contaminated with a bit of protein make these less than compelling experimental result.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Watson and Crick did not perform any experiments. Their conclusions were based on research of others. Erwin Chargaff noted that the concentrations of guanine and cytosine were always equal in DNA. Likewise, the concentrations of adenine and thymine were equal. Rosalind Franklin and Maurice Wilkins used X-ray crystallography to study DNA. From these structures, Watson and Crick deduced that DNA had repeating structures (nucleotides), the DNA was of a constant width and double-stranded.
phenomenonA Watson and Crick based their model on data from Erwin Chargaff showing an approximate relationship between the concentrations of A and T and G and C, and on X-ray diffraction data from Rosalind Franklin.
phenomenonA[comment] Watson and Crick found that guanine and cytosine form three hydrogen bonds. The hydrogen donors are the NH2 group attached to carbon 2 of adenine, the hydrogen attached to nitrogen 1 or adenine and the NH2 group attached to carbon 4 of cytosine. These are accepted by the oxygen group attached to carbon 2 of cytosine, nitrogen 3 of cytosine, and the oxygen atom attached to carbon 6 of guanine.
phenomenonB Experiments by Avery, McCarty and MacLeod conclusively demonstrated that DNA was the genetic material.
phenomenonB[comment] Originally, Fred Griffith set the tone for the final proof that DNA was the genetic material. Working with lethal and non-lethal strains of the Streptococcus pneumoniae, he showed that a factor from a lethal strain could convert a non-lethal strain to a lethal strain. Because his factor was able to convert one phenotype to another, Griffith called this factor the transforming principle. Avery, MacLeod, and McCarty studied this factor and their experiments proved that the transforming principle was DNA.

explainConcepts[SQ001] The experiments conducted by Avery and his colleagues were definitive, but many scientists were very reluctant to accept DNA (rather than proteins) as the genetic material. The clincher was provided in 1952 by Alfred Hershey and Martha Chase with the use of the phage (virus) T2.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Hershey and Chase showed that when bacteriophages, which are composed of DNA and protein, infect bacteria, their DNA enters the host bacterial cell, but most of their protein does not.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The second set of clues available to Watson and Crick came from work done several years earlier by Erwin Chargaff. Studying a large selection of DNAs from different organisms, Chargaff established certain empirical rules about the amounts of each component of DNA:
phenomenonA Watson and Crick based their model on data from Erwin Chargaff showing an approximate relationship between the concentrations of A and T and G and C, and on X-ray diffraction data from Rosalind Franklin.
phenomenonA[comment] The structure that Watson and Crick derived from these clues is a double helix, which looks rather like two interlocked bedsprings. Each bedspring (helix) is a chain of nucleotides held together by phosphodiester bonds, in which a phosphate group forms a bridge between −OH groups on two adjacent sugar residues.
phenomenonB Watson and Crick based their model on data from Erwin Chargaff showing an approximate relationship between the concentrations of A and T and G and C, and on X-ray diffraction data from Rosalind Franklin.
phenomenonB[comment] Erwin Chargaff proposed two main rules in his lifetime which were appropriately named Chargaff's rules. The first and best known achievement was to show that in natural DNA the number of guanine units equals the number of cytosine units and the number of adenine units equals the number of thymine units.

explainConcepts[SQ001] The big question during this time period for geneticist was whether DNA or Protein was the biomolecule responsible for heredity. First, Avery, McCarty, and Macleod grew IIIS cells in a liquid culture. They then centrifuged the cells and heat killed them. They then extracted the carbohydrates, the proteins, and the lipids. They then treated the filtered cells with different chemicals to arrive at the conclusion that DNA was the "transforming principle."
explainConcepts[SQ002] Hershey and Chase used radioisotopes to label both the protein and DNA of the phage head. Only the radioisotopes found on DNA were recovered in the progeny. This provided even more convincing evidence that DNA was the heritable material, not protein.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Based on previous data, Watson and Crick made there model consistent with what was already known about DNA. From looking at the data, Watson and Crick concluded that A is proportional to t and that G is proportional to C. Also, the X-Ray diffraction analysis suggested that the DNA molecule was some sort of helix, so based on what was known at the time, Watson and Crick built there model.
phenomenonA Watson and Crick based their model on data from Erwin Chargaff showing an approximate relationship between the concentrations of A and T and G and C, and on X-ray diffraction data from Rosalind Franklin.
phenomenonA[comment] Knowing this information, we can tell when looking at a genome, where exactly a mutation occurred, since we know exactly what is supposed to pair with what.
phenomenonB Hershey-Chase experiments extended the finding that DNA was the genetic material to bacteriophage.
phenomenonB[comment] Had it not been for the Hershey-Chase experiment during this time, enough evidence may not have been present to convince the science world that DNA was truly the biomolecule responsible for heredity.

explainConcepts[SQ001] I do not know many details about this experiment that was conducted by Avery, McCarty, and MacLeod, besides the basic set-up of the experiment and that this experiment was the important basis that proved that DNA is the hereditary molecule. The group utilized strains of Pneumoccous Bacteria and allowed the process of transformation to occur and one by one destroyed each macromolecule within groups of flasks. The use of enzymes to breakdown lipids, RNA/DNA, proteins and carbohydrates allowed the researchers to determine if the process of transformation was still occurring. Through various, arduous trials, they were able to conclude that DNA is the genetic material since after the destruction of DNA/RNA transformation ceased unlike in the other scenarios during the destruction of other macromolecules in which transformation continues to occur.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Hershey and Chase radioactively labeled the bacteriophages with radioactive Phosphorous and radioactive Sulfur. These isotopes were specifically chosen since the researchers knew that the viruses had only a protein compartment and a DNA compartment, but they didn't know which of the two macromolecules allow the production of more bacteriophages. The radioactive sulfur labels the proteins because of the formation of disulfide bonds during the tertiary structure of proteins and the radioactive phosphorous labels the DNA strand due to the phosphate sugar backbones present. Once the bacteriophages were given ample time to infect bacteria, the mixture of the cells and the bacteriophages were then centrifuged. The centrifuged results showed that the pellets contained radioactive phosphorous inside the bacterial cell while the radioactive sulfur was found simply floating closer to the top which became the supernatant. This fascinating experiment was conducted multiple times and supported that DNA was in fact the hereditary material in bacteriophages.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Watson and Crick are two renowned scientists that pieced the model of the DNA molecule together by gathering information from other researchers. They were able to construct a DNA model that was anti-parallel, double helix with the nitrogenous bases on the interior due to their hydrophobic tendencies and the phosphate sugar backbone facing on the outside due to their hydrophilic nature. Chargaff came about an astounding phenomena that later became to be known as Chargaff's Rules. These rules state that the proportion of adenine to thymine is almost equivalent and the proportion of guanine to cytosine is almost equivalent, but the proportions of adenine and thymine to guanine and cytosine is not necessarily equivalent. Furthermore, he determined that different species had variations in the proportions of these 4 nitrogenous bases. However, Rosalind Franklin's story contrasts highly from Chargaff in the sense that she was not able to publish her findings. Franklin specialized in X-Ray crystallography patterns which helped her determined the properties of the DNA molecule from the width to the length of the DNA in Angstroms. Her famous image (Picture 31) showed that DNA was a double helix with a phosphate sugar backbone on the exterior and the nitrogenous bases connected on the interior. Her work was shared with Watson and Crick without her attention, thus she did not get any accreditation on her work until years later.
phenomenonA Experiments by Avery, McCarty and MacLeod conclusively demonstrated that DNA was the genetic material.
phenomenonA[comment] I am really interested in Avery, McCarty, and MacLeod's experiment. I hope to learn more about this experiment especially the specifics during this experiment as to how certain enzymes were able to digest or destroy certain macromolecules. I just find this experiment very interesting since they were able to use very little information provided in addition to Griffith's results with bacteria to conclude such a drastic change in science and societal claims that DNA was the genetic material and not proteins.
phenomenonB Hershey-Chase experiments extended the finding that DNA was the genetic material to bacteriophage.
phenomenonB[comment] I find this experiment with bacteriophages were fascinating since Hershey and Chase were able to determine that the two isotopes radioactive Sulfur and radioactive Phosphorous is found in proteins and DNA, respectively, and the labels do not overlap which could interfere with the original point of this experiment. I am curious as to finding out what information the researchers had previous to their experimentation.

The fact that the smooth strain are less susceptible to being annihilated before infection, these strains are the ones that cause Pneumonia rather than the R strain.

The X-ray data showed the molecule to be helical). They did this by using two radioactive dyes, one that binds to protein molecules, and one that binds to DNA molecules. They then looked at which of the two dyes ended up inside of the host cell. The result was, of course, that the DNA molecules had made it into the host cell.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Watson and Crick were essentially the first ones to see the big picture on DNA structure. They were able to look at data from a wide array of sources and bring that information together in order to make conclusions. For example, they used data from Erwin Chargaff and Rosalind Franklin. After pooling all of this information, they were able to conclude that DNA was in the shape of a double helix with base pairs of A/T and G/C.

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that the experiments by Avery, McCarty, and MacLeod reported that they had obtained the transforming principle in a purified state and that it was definitely genetic material. They began their isolation process with large quantities of liquid cultures of type IIIS virulent cells. The ells were centrifuged, collected, and heat killed. Following homogenization and extractions with DOC, they obtained a soluble filtrate that retained the ability to induce transformation of type IIR avirulent cells. Protein was removed from active filtrate and polysaccharides were enzymatically digested and removed. Finally, precipitation of fibrous mass still retained the ability to transform the type IIR avirulent cells which lead to the discovery of the "active factor" being genetic material.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I undestand that the Hershey-Chase experiments is the second major piece of evidence supporting that DNA is genetic material. They discovered that T2 phages concept of approximately 50% protein and 50% DNA, infection is initiated by absorption of the phage by its tail fibers to the bacterial cell, and the production of new viruses occurs within the bacterial cell. Using radioisotopes, they labeled molecular components of phages during infection. Because DNA contains P but not S, S labels protein. Following these labels resulted in the conclusion that DNA was the genetic material in a bacteriophage.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that Watson and Crick determined the double helix structure of DNA due to several factors. Their model included 2 long polynucleotide chains coiled around a central axis, forming a double helix. The two chains are antiparallel and the bases of both chains are flat structures lying perpendicular to the axis (they are "stacked" on one another). The nitrogenous bases of opposite chains are paired as the result of the formation of hydrogen bonds (2 between A & T, and 3 between G & C). Each helix is the length of a series of 10 base pairs and the larger major groove alternates with the smaller minor groove. The double helix has a diameter pf 2.0 nm.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that Griffith's experiment was the first experiment suggesting that bacteria are capable of transferring genetic information through a process known as transformation. He used 2 strains of pneumococcus bacteria to infect mice; a type IIIS (smooth) which was virulent and a type IIR which was nonvirulent. The IIIS strain covered itself with a polysaccharide capsule that protected it from the host's immune system, resulting in death of the host, while the IIR strain did not have the protective capsule and was defeated by the host's immune system. In the experiment, bacteria from the IIIS strain were killed by heat and their remains were added to IIR strain bacteria. While neither alone harmed the mince, the combination was able to ill its host. This concluded that the type IIR strain had been "transformed" into the lethal IIIS strain by a transforming principle which is DNA.

groupTime440 39.47

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Using mice and viral strains, Avery, McCarty and MacLeod proved that DNA was the genetic material. They proved this by inject mice with either a rough strain, smooth strain, heat killed smooth strain, or combination of rough strain and heat killed smooth strain. The results were that those with just the rough strain lived. Those with just smooth strain died. Those with heat killed smooth strain lived. Those with the combination of rough strain with heat killed smooth strain died. This showed that even though the lethal strain had been heat killed, when its DNA came in contact with that of the rough strain, it made the rough strain lethal.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Hershey and Chase used bacteriophages to prove further that Dna was genetic material. They did this by using radioactive sulfur and phosphorus. One bacteriophage had the radioactive sulfur, and "cold" DNA. After centrifugation the product was radioactive sulfur labeled proteins but no radioactive label on the DNA. The second phage contained the radioactive phosphorus and "hot" DNA. After centrifugation this result was no radioactive label in the protein but there was a radioactive phosphorus label in the DNA.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Watson and Crick combined Franklin's ray diffraction data, which proved that DNA had a double helix structure, and Chargaff's data which showed the approximate number of A and T to G and C. By combining these two sets of data, Watson and Crick were able to build a three dimensional model of DNA matching up the bases to form a double helix structure.
phenomenonA Watson and Crick based their model on data from Erwin Chargaff showing an approximate relationship between the concentrations of A and T and G and C, and on X-ray diffraction data from Rosalind Franklin.
phenomenonA[comment] This topic interests me because for quite some time, Rosalind Franklin did not get the proper attention for her discovery. She was on the same track and slightly ahead of Watson and Crick before they pretty much stole her data to use.
phenomenonB Experiments by Avery, McCarty and MacLeod conclusively demonstrated that DNA was the genetic material.
phenomenonB[comment] After reading through this experiment I was interested by the fact that even though the lethal smooth strain was heat killed, when combined with a non lethal rough strain, the combo still killed the mice. It reminded me of how bacteria are becoming antibiotic resistant but the same process.

groupTime440 30.14

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The experiments by Avery, McCarty, and Macleod showed that DNA was conclusively the hereditary material by putting cells in a liquid medium culture. Then centrifuging them followed by heat. They then removed all carbohydrates, lipids, and proteins and tested the remaining cells with different enzymes (protease, ribonuclease, and deoxyribonuclease) to see under what conditions would transformation occurs. Transformation happened in three of the four experiment types showing that DNA had to be the source of genetic material instead of RNA or proteins. (The fourth was the control.)
explainConcepts[SQ002] The Hershey-Chase experiments extended the finding of Avery, McCarty, and Macleod by showing that DNA was the genetic material to bacteriophage. They proved this by using radioactive phosphorus and sulfur. This worked because it was able to label just the DNA because DNA contains phosphorus which protein does not while protein contains sulfur which DNA does not. Therefore, Hershey and Chase were able to observe the fact that bacteriophages were absorbing some of the P-labeled DNA while pretty much all of the S-labeled proteins remained outside the cell.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Watson and Crick used the data from Erwin Chargaff that showed an approximate relationship between the concentrations of A and T and G and C. The model they proposed suggested that DNA was a double helix consisting of two antiparallel strands. The model also suggested that the two strands were 0.34 nm apart and that the nitrogen bases are paired as a result of the formation of hydrogen bonds (A-T and G-C).
phenomenonA Experiments by Avery, McCarty and MacLeod conclusively demonstrated that DNA was the genetic material.
phenomenonA[comment] The experiments by Avery, McCarty, and Macleod were able to conclusively show that DNA was the genetic material. This is particularly interesting to me because that has been the basis for everything we've learned about in genetics and heredity and allows us to have a much better understanding of genes and how they are passed. This also allows us to learn more about genetic defects that could be encoded in human DNA which to me is the most interesting biological phenomenon we have discussed thus far.
phenomenonB Hershey-Chase experiments extended the finding that DNA was the genetic material to bacteriophage.
phenomenonB[comment] The Hershey-Chase experiment was able to end the knowledge that DNA was the genetic material to bacteriophages by using radioactively labeled phosphorus and sulfur. To me, this is interesting because it sheds light onto the biological phenomenon of bacterial conjugation as a source of genetic diversity, when before this class I had mostly only thought of sexual reproduction as a source for diversity.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Avery, McCarty, and MacLeod performed an experiment by isolating strains of virulent IIIS strains. Then they obtained a transformation inducing IIIS filtrate. They treated the IIIS with IIR cells and an IIIS filtrate treated with protease, RNase, or DNase then studied the resulting medium's material to see if transformation had occurred. When the protein and RNA was destroyed, transformation still occurred. When DNA was destroyed, no transformation occurred. Leading the scientists to conclude that DNA was the transforming genetic material.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Hershey and Chase used radioisotopes for phosphorous and sulfur to label DNA (which included P but not S) and proteins (which included S but not P). Then they tested cells and bacteriophages during infection to see which molecule (DNA, protein, or both) was being injected into the cell to direct reproduction. P-labeled DNA was found to be injected into the cells while the S-labeled proteins remained behind in the empty bacteriophage coats. This led Hershey and Chase to conclude that DNA was the genetic material of bacteriophages.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Watson and Crick were able to combines the findings of other talented scientists in the race to uncover the structure of genetic material. Based off Chargaff's, they knew how base pairs went together in DNA strands. And after obtaining X-ray diffraction data from the extensive work of Rosalind Franklins and an explanation that the structure was helical, they were able to create and accurate double helix structure of DNA.
phenomenonA Watson and Crick based their model on data from Erwin Chargaff showing an approximate relationship between the concentrations of A and T and G and C, and on X-ray diffraction data from Rosalind Franklin.
phenomenonA[comment] There have been studies of a 'DNA untwister" that can be used as a cancer suppressor. As someone who hopes to be a pediatric oncologist, this is highly interesting to me.
phenomenonB
phenomenonB[comment] I cannot think of another way any of these can be tied into a genetic phenomenon that I know much about.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The Avery-McCarty-Macleod experiements proved that DNA was the genetic material. The trio also discovered the pathway of transformation. They used 2 different bacteria strains of the same bacterial species, R and S strains. The S strain was pathogenic and the R strain was not pathogenic. He incubated heat-killed S strain and living R strain and injected this into a mice. The mixture was found to be pathogenic killing the mice. When bacteria was isolated from these mice however, living S strain was found proving that some factor of the S strain was assimilated in the R strain transforming them into S strain bacteria. Because this transformation was inherited, they assumed that this factor was the genetic material.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Hershey and Chase conducted early experiments which demonstrated that DNA was the genetic material of bacteriophages. They did this by using T2 bacteriophages, which is a strain of viruse that infect bacteria by injecting their attaching to the cell and injecting their DNA into the cell cytoplasm. The pair labeled phage DNA with radioactive phosphorous-32 and labeled phage protein with sulfur-35. They then used E. Coli cells to track the transmission of these radioactive elements. They found that the phosphorous was found within the cells and the sulfur was found outside the cells proving that the DNA was the genetic material.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The experiments done by Watson and Crick provided a model of DNA structure. The two had been working on their model when they received data collected by Franklin proving that DNA had a helical structure. With this information along with the findings of Chargaff, which showed that the concentrations of A=T and G=C, Watson and Crick were able to determine the shape and structure of DNA. This finding has often been considered the most important biological discovery of all time.
phenomenonA Watson and Crick based their model on data from Erwin Chargaff showing an approximate relationship between the concentrations of A and T and G and C, and on X-ray diffraction data from Rosalind Franklin.
phenomenonA[comment] Watson and Crick are the two individuals who are given credit for creating the first accurate model of DNA's double-helical, complex strucuture. They were able to come up with this model through the compilation of their own work and those findings done by Chargaff and Franklin.
phenomenonB Hershey-Chase experiments extended the finding that DNA was the genetic material to bacteriophage.
phenomenonB[comment] Hershey-chase used T2 bacteria and radioactive sulfur and phosphorous to prove that the heritable, genetic material of bacteriophages is DNA.

explainConcepts[SQ001] Avery, McCarty, and MacLeod began their experiment with large quantities of liquid cultures of type IIIS virulent cells. Thier experiment was answering the question of what molecule served as the transforming principle. The virulent cells were centrifuged, collected, and heat killed. They were able to induce type IIR avirulent cells by extractions. The experiment concluded that DNA was the fundamental unit for transformation
explainConcepts[SQ002] The Hershey-Chase experiment also helped support that DNA was the genetic material. The evidence was from studying E. Coli and one of its infecting viruses bacteriophage T2 (phage). Hershey and Chase ran a bunch of experiments and several of the experiments established the independent function of the phage protein and nucleic acid in the reproduction process associated with bacterial cell. Through their experiment they were able to find out a lot of information. Their experiment along with Avery provided evidence that DNA was the molecule responsible for heredity.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The key to the model they proposed is specifically the base pairing. Chargaff's data had led Watson and Crick to believe that A was equal in amount to T and G was equal in amount to C. Watson and Crick realized this and these pairs were a result from hydrogen bonds between base pairs. This also provided the chemical stability necessary to hold the two chains together. Their model had the features of a double helix, two long polynucleotide chains that were coiled, two chains that were antiparallel, C-5' to C-3'. There were also other features that were present in their model.
phenomenonA Experiments by Avery, McCarty and MacLeod conclusively demonstrated that DNA was the genetic material.
phenomenonA[comment] The experiment done by Avery, McCarty, and MacLeod was able to give us further knowledge that DNA was the genetic material that makes up many things. This helps the knowledge we have on diseases that are passed down.
phenomenonB Watson and Crick based their model on data from Erwin Chargaff showing an approximate relationship between the concentrations of A and T and G and C, and on X-ray diffraction data from Rosalind Franklin.
phenomenonB[comment] By knowing the knowledge of what the DNA looks like and what the base pairs are. People will be able to detect if there is a mutation. (Maybe T pairing with C). We will be able to detect the source of some problems people may have.

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand the experiments done by Avery, MacLeod, and McCarty lead us to believe that DNA was the genetic material. I understand that their experiment was used to text for transformation. They began their experiment by isolating large quantities of liquid cultures of the type IIIS virulent cells. The cells were centrifuged, collected, and heat killed, Following, several extractions were done and the they obtained a soluble filtrate that retained the ability to induce transformation of type IIR avirulent cells. Proteins were removed from the active filtrate by several chloroform extractions, and polysaccharides were enzymatically digested and removed. Their final conformation was that DNA was the fundamental unit for transformation.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that the Hershey-Chase experiment led us to believe that DNA was the genetic material to bacteriophage. Several of their experiments clearly established the independent functions of phage protein and nucleic acid in the reproduction process associated with the bacterial cell. Through their experiment they were able to indicate that the protein of the phage coat remains outside the host cell and is not involved in directing the production of the new phage. Most important phage DNA enters the host cell and directs phage reproduction. They were able to demonstrate that the genetic material in phage T2 is DNA, not protein.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that Watson and Crick's model was not based purely on their knowledge, but knowledge of other scientists. They were not the only one that should have taken credit for their model. Their model has the features of two long polynucleotide chains that were coiled around a central axis that formed a right-handed double helix. Their model also was antiparallel going from C-5' to C-3'. The nitrogenous bases of opposite chains are paired as the result of the formation of hydrogen bonds; in DNA only A paris with T and G pairs with C.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Frederick Griffith studied two strains of the bacterium Streptococcus pneumoniae. Bacteria of the S (smooth) strain can cause pneumonia in mice; they are pathogenic because they have an outer capsule that protects them from an animal's defense system. Bacteria of the R (rough) strain lack a capsule and are nonpathogenic. To test for the trait of pathogenicity, Griffith injected mice with the two strains. He concluded that the living R bacteria had been transformed into pathogenic S bacteria by an unknown, heritable substance from the dead S cells that allowed the R cells to make capsules. Only when DNA was allowed to remain active did transformation occur. Through this experiment we were able to conclude that DAN was the hereditary material

groupTime440 55.1

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] he Avery–MacLeod–McCarty experiment was an experimental demonstration, reported in 1944 by Oswald Avery, Colin MacLeod, and Maclyn McCarty, that DNA is the substance that causes bacterial transformation, in an era when it had been widely believed that it was proteins that served the function of carrying genetic information. It was the culmination of research in the 1930s and early 1940s at the Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research to purify and characterize the "transforming principle" responsible for the transformation phenomenon first described in Griffith's experiment of 1928: killed Streptococcus pneumoniae of the virulent strain type III-S, when injected along with living but non-virulent type II-R pneumococci, resulted in a deadly infection of type III-S pneumococci.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The Hershey–Chase experiments were a series of experiments conducted in 1952 by Alfred Hershey and Martha Chase that helped to confirm that DNA is the genetic material. While DNA had been known to biologists since 1869, many scientists still assumed at the time that proteins carried the information for inheritance because DNA appeared simpler than proteins. In their experiments, Hershey and Chase showed that when bacteriophages, which are composed of DNA and protein, infect bacteria, their DNA enters the host bacterial cell, but most of their protein does not.
explainConcepts[SQ003] "Molecular Structure of Nucleic Acids: A Structure for Deoxyribose Nucleic Acid" was an article published by Francis Crick and James D. Watson in the scientific journal Nature. It was the first publication which described the discovery of the double helix structure of DNA, using X-ray diffraction and the mathematics of a helix transform.
phenomenonA Experiments by Avery, McCarty and MacLeod conclusively demonstrated that DNA was the genetic material.
phenomenonA[comment] We see the phenomena in nature every day within the laws of evolution and in todays genetic medicine that has been the betterment of millions of lives
phenomenonB Hershey-Chase experiments extended the finding that DNA was the genetic material to bacteriophage.
phenomenonB[comment] This isi an outstanding discovery because it lead the way in our understanding of bacteriophages. That they can collect peices of DNA of the cell that they were born of. How they replicate and infect host cells. All of this is due to our knowledge gain by this experiment

It was the culmination of research in the 1930s and early 1940s at the Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research to purify and characterize the "transforming principle" responsible for the transformation phenomenon first described in Griffith's experiment of 1928: killed Streptococcus pneumoniae of the virulent strain type III-S, when injected along with living but non-virulent type II-R pneumococci, resulted in a deadly infection of type III-S pneumococci.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] The Hershey–Chase experiments were a series of experiments conducted in 1952 by Alfred Hershey and Martha Chase that helped to confirm that DNA is the genetic material. While DNA had been known to biologists since 1869, many scientists still assumed at the time that proteins carried the information for inheritance because DNA appeared simpler than proteins. In their experiments, Hershey and Chase showed that when bacteriophages, which are composed of DNA and protein, infect bacteria, their DNA enters the host bacterial cell, but most of their protein does not.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] "Molecular Structure of Nucleic Acids: A Structure for Deoxyribose Nucleic Acid" was an article published by Francis Crick and James D. Watson in the scientific journal Nature. It was the first publication which described the discovery of the double helix structure of DNA, using X-ray diffraction and the mathematics of a helix transform.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Griffith's experiment, reported in 1928, identified that some "transforming principle" in pneumococcal bacteria could transform them from one type to another. Griffith, a British medical officer, had spent years applying serological typing to cases of pneumonia, a frequently fatal disease in the early 20th century. He found that multiple types—some virulent and some non-virulent—were often present over the course of a clinical case of pneumonia, and thought that one type might change into another (rather than simply multiple types being present all along). In testing that possibility, he found that transformation could occur when dead bacteria of a virulent type and live bacteria of a non-virulent type were both injected in mice: the mice would develop a fatal infection (normally only caused by live bacteria of the virulent type) and die, and virulent bacteria could be isolated from such infected mice.
